<div id=3D"sbo-rt-content" style=3D"transform: none;"><div class=3D"annotat=
or-wrapper"><div class=3D"chap">
<h2 class=3D"chtitle"><a id=3D"h36"></a><a id=3D"page_95"></a><span class=
=3D"cn">4</span> FRAMEWORKS, TOOLS AND TECHNIQUES</h2>
</div>
<p class=3D"noindent">Since business analysis is an established discipline,=
 there are a range of frameworks, tools and techniques that are available t=
o BAs. It is rarely necessary to reinvent the wheel, and there are many use=
ful resources on which BAs can draw for inspiration. Frameworks provide use=
ful patterns for a practitioner to use, but the way that a framework is app=
lied will vary depending on the context. An urgent need to respond to a sud=
den security concern may, for example, be handled differently from a larger=
, longer-term organisational change.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">This chapter signposts key frameworks from both BCS a=
nd IIBA<sup>=C2=AE</sup> and elaborates on the contexts in which they might=
 be used. The following frameworks and models are discussed:</p>
<div class=3D"top">
<p class=3D"bull"><span class=3D"bul">=E2=80=A2</span> Business Analysis Pr=
ocess Model (BCS);</p>
<p class=3D"bull"><span class=3D"bul">=E2=80=A2</span> Requirements Enginee=
ring Framework (BCS);</p>
<p class=3D"bull"><span class=3D"bul">=E2=80=A2</span> BABOK<sup>=C2=AE</su=
p> Knowledge Areas (IIBA<sup>=C2=AE</sup>).</p>
</div>
<p class=3D"noindent">A list of commonly used BA techniques is also provide=
d, along with a brief description of each technique. <span class=3D"bold">T=
he intention of this chapter is to signpost other resources.</span> Whilst =
an introduction to each framework is provided and each technique is succinc=
tly introduced, there is much more written about each of these in other BCS=
 and IIBA<sup>=C2=AE</sup> resources which are mentioned within the chapter=
. The chapter concludes with a brief reminder that interpersonal skills are=
 crucial within business analysis; even though the focus of this chapter is=
 frameworks and techniques, we should keep interpersonal skills firmly in m=
ind too.</p>
<h3 class=3D"h3" id=3D"sec25"><a id=3D"h37"></a><a id=3D"page_96"></a>FRAME=
WORKS: AVOIDING PAINTING BY NUMBERS</h3>
<p class=3D"noindent">The very nature of business analysis means that it is=
 not possible to take an entirely formulaic and repeatable approach. There =
is no single =E2=80=98paint-by-numbers=E2=80=99 approach that will be effec=
tive in every single conceivable situation. Re-engineering a procurement pr=
ocess in a small and efficient business would, for example, be a very diffe=
rent analysis engagement from a project aiming to implement an electronic p=
atient record system in a hospital.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">The tools and techniques that are used (and the analy=
sis artefacts that are produced) will be guided by the context in which the=
 analysis is undertaken. BAs have a broad set of tools and techniques at th=
eir disposal, and part of the analyst=E2=80=99s job is to choose the best t=
ool for the situation (and to be prepared to change approach if a particula=
r tool or technique does not work in a given situation). Contextual and ext=
ernal factors =E2=80=93 such as available budget, time pressure, risk and c=
ulture =E2=80=93 can affect the suitability of particular tools or can mean=
 that they have to be used in a particular way.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">However, using a set of unrelated tools in isolation =
is unlikely to lead to the most effective outcome. Not only do analysts nee=
d to think holistically about the business situation which they are investi=
gating but they also need to think holistically about how the overall set o=
f analysis tasks will be completed. A number of complementary frameworks ha=
ve emerged which can be of great assistance. Two of particular relevance ar=
e BCS=E2=80=99s Business Analysis Process Model and Requirements Engineerin=
g Framework and another is the collection of Knowledge Areas from within II=
BA<sup>=C2=AE</sup>=E2=80=99s <span class=3D"italic">BABOK<sup>=C2=AE</sup>=
 Guide</span>.</p>
<h4 class=3D"h4">Business Analysis Process Model</h4>
<p class=3D"noindent">BCS=E2=80=99s Business Analysis Process Model (from P=
aul, Cadle and Yeates 2014; see <a href=3D"https://learning.oreilly.com/lib=
rary/view/business-analyst-/9781780174280/14_chapter04.xhtml#fig4-1">Figure=
 4.1</a>) is designed to provide high-level, flexible guidance on how a bus=
iness analysis engagement is typically conducted. The stages of the process=
 model are relevant whatever the initiative: for very small initiatives or =
<a id=3D"page_97"></a>those where there is a clearly provable problem and s=
olution, a lightweight approach might be taken. Other initiatives where the=
 landscape is less clear may require significantly more analysis work up fr=
ont. The model supports either approach and leaves the practitioner and the=
 project team to select the right tools for any given situation.</p>
<div class=3D"border1"></div>
<p class=3D"captionf"><a id=3D"page_98"></a><a id=3D"fig4-1"></a><span clas=
s=3D"cap"><span class=3D"bold">Figure 4.1</span></span> <span class=3D"bold=
">Business Analysis Process Model</span> (Reproduced by permission of Assis=
t Knowledge Development Ltd)</p>
<p class=3D"image"><img src=3D"https://learning.oreilly.com/library/view/bu=
siness-analyst-/9781780174280/images/fig4-1.jpg" alt=3D"" width=3D"1030" he=
ight=3D"346" data-mfp-src=3D"/library/view/business-analyst-/9781780174280/=
images/fig4-1.jpg"></p>
<p class=3D"noindent">A BA may join this model at any stage or may progress=
 through certain stages in parallel or iteratively. In some cases, one sing=
le =E2=80=98stage=E2=80=99 might be the assignment (e.g. an initial report =
to investigate the situation). Whatever the assignment, the business contex=
t must be kept front of mind at all times =E2=80=93 this will help the prac=
titioner to select relevant tools and guide relevant activities.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">A brief description of each stage is shown in <a href=
=3D"https://learning.oreilly.com/library/view/business-analyst-/97817801742=
80/14_chapter04.xhtml#tab4-1">Table 4.1</a>.</p>
<h5 class=3D"h5"><span class=3D"bold"><span class=3D"italic">Example</span>=
</span></h5>
<p class=3D"noindenta">The following example illustrates each stage. Imagin=
e conducting business analysis for an online book retailer. It is crucial t=
o have a continual awareness of the <span class=3D"bold">business context.<=
/span> External events, such as a change in data privacy regulation, could =
have a vast impact on how the organisation operates and may necessitate new=
 change projects or changes to existing projects. Equally, being aware of t=
he organisation=E2=80=99s own stated strategy is crucial. A retailer that s=
trives to offer the lowest possible prices to its customers may pursue very=
 different projects from one that is seeking to stock luxury goods with =E2=
=80=98value-added=E2=80=99 services such as personalised recommendations.</=
p>
<div class=3D"border1"></div>
<p class=3D"captiont"><a id=3D"tab4-1"></a><span class=3D"cap"><span class=
=3D"bold">Table 4.1</span></span> <span class=3D"bold">Stages of the Busine=
ss Analysis Process Model</span></p>
<table style=3D"width:100%" class=3D"table-se">
<colgroup>
<col style=3D"width:20%">
<col style=3D"width:80%">
</colgroup>
<thead>
<tr>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s1"><span class=3D"bold">Sta=
ge</span></td>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s1"><span class=3D"bold">Bri=
ef Description</span></td>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">Business context</td>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">Involves:
<p class=3D"bull-s"><span class=3D"bul-s">=E2=80=A2</span> gaining and main=
taining an understanding of the external and internal business environments=
;</p>
<p class=3D"bull-s"><span class=3D"bul-s">=E2=80=A2</span> maintaining an a=
wareness of existing organisational strengths and weaknesses;</p>
<p class=3D"bull-s"><span class=3D"bul-s">=E2=80=A2</span> maintaining a go=
od understanding of the organisational strategy and of how potential projec=
ts and programmes align with it.</p>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">Investigate situation</td=
>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">Involves:
<p class=3D"bull-s"><span class=3D"bul-s">=E2=80=A2</span> conducting an in=
itial investigation of the problematic situation;</p>
<p class=3D"bull-s"><span class=3D"bul-s">=E2=80=A2</span> conducting an in=
itial scope of the analysis work;</p>
<p class=3D"bull-s"><span class=3D"bul-s">=E2=80=A2</span> documenting the =
business situation.</p>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">Consider perspectives</td=
>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">Involves:
<p class=3D"bull-s"><span class=3D"bul-s">=E2=80=A2</span> identifying, cat=
egorising and planning to engage with stakeholders =E2=80=93 potentially in=
cluding stakeholders both inside and outside the organisation;</p>
<p class=3D"bull-s"><span class=3D"bul-s">=E2=80=A2</span> assessing the va=
rious worldviews and perspectives held by stakeholders;</p>
<p class=3D"bull-s"><span class=3D"bul-s">=E2=80=A2</span> creating models =
based on stakeholder perspectives (conceptual models such as business activ=
ity models);</p>
<p class=3D"bull-s"><span class=3D"bul-s">=E2=80=A2</span> seeking =E2=80=
=98accommodation=E2=80=99 or, where possible, consensus between competing p=
erspectives.</p>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s"><a id=3D"page_99"></a>Ana=
lyse needs</td>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">Involves:
<p class=3D"bull-s"><span class=3D"bul-s">=E2=80=A2</span> conducting a gap=
 analysis to compare the desired state and current state;</p>
<p class=3D"bull-s"><span class=3D"bul-s">=E2=80=A2</span> conducting furth=
er, more detailed examination of the current situation and processes.</p>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">Evaluate options</td>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">Involves:
<p class=3D"bull-s"><span class=3D"bul-s">=E2=80=A2</span> generating a lis=
t of potential improvement opportunities;</p>
<p class=3D"bull-s"><span class=3D"bul-s">=E2=80=A2</span> assessing the fe=
asibility of each option;</p>
<p class=3D"bull-s"><span class=3D"bul-s">=E2=80=A2</span> creating justifi=
cation and an artefact that supports decision making =E2=80=93 typically a =
business case.</p>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">Define requirements</td>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">Involves:
<p class=3D"bull-s"><span class=3D"bul-s">=E2=80=A2</span> eliciting, analy=
sing and validating requirements;</p>
<p class=3D"bull-s"><span class=3D"bul-s">=E2=80=A2</span> creating require=
ments documentation, including relevant models;</p>
<p class=3D"bull-s"><span class=3D"bul-s">=E2=80=A2</span> using the Requir=
ements Engineering Framework.</p>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p class=3D"noindent">Our analysis may start with a somewhat unclear brief =
from a senior stakeholder in the organisation. Perhaps there has been a not=
iceable drop in revenue but there is no obvious reason why. In some cases, =
stakeholders may have a very <a id=3D"page_100"></a>firm idea of the soluti=
on =E2=80=93 but it will be for the BA to ensure that the problem space is =
fully understood (and that the most appropriate solution is recommended). T=
he first step is to <span class=3D"bold">investigate the situation.</span> =
This may involve a range of initial interviews, workshops and perhaps even =
observation. We will start to gauge who the likely stakeholders are, the ar=
eas involved, and the political and social dynamics that exist. This stage =
is as much about assessing and understanding the informal elements of a pro=
blem situation as it is about assessing and understanding those that are fo=
rmal. Knowing that particular teams do (or do not) get along is very useful=
!</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">Having investigated the situation, it is now appropri=
ate to undertake further deliberate stakeholder identification and analysis=
. This starts with consciously scouring the stakeholder landscape, assessin=
g who might need to be involved, and assessing who holds power and interest=
 in the situation. Stakeholders are then typically categorised, with those =
with high power and influence being seen as the key players =E2=80=93 but w=
ith no stakeholder being completely ignored. Understanding our stakeholder =
landscape enables us to <span class=3D"bold">consider perspectives</span>. =
In our online retailer example, we may find that two directors have two ver=
y different perspectives, such as:</p>
<div class=3D"top">
<p class=3D"bull"><span class=3D"bul">=E2=80=A2</span> <span class=3D"bold"=
>Director A:</span> =E2=80=98Our business exists to sell books via a websit=
e, in doing so contributing towards profit and dividends for its owners.=E2=
=80=99</p>
<p class=3D"bull"><span class=3D"bul">=E2=80=A2</span> <span class=3D"bold"=
>Director B:</span> =E2=80=98Our business exists to impart knowledge by sel=
ling books, in doing so contributing towards a better educated society, whi=
lst also making profits for the business owners.=E2=80=99</p>
</div>
<p class=3D"noindent">These perspectives may seem similar, but they are suf=
ficiently different that we are likely to see continual conflict =E2=80=93 =
but this is often the kind of conflict that is implicit and bubbles up from=
 time to time in seemingly unpredictable ways. Director A will likely be pu=
rsuing projects that cut costs and increase revenue, whereas Director B may=
 well favour those that widen the accessibility of books (and Director B ma=
y have less of <a id=3D"page_101"></a>a focus on profits). There are a rang=
e of analysis techniques that can help us to analyse these perspectives and=
 to consider and model the different activities that would exist if either =
perspective were to be made a reality. These conceptual models can be used =
to drive a consensus or state of accommodation between stakeholders with co=
nflicting views =E2=80=93 consensus is clearly the best outcome, but in con=
tentious situations the key is to reach an agreement that everyone can live=
 with and sign up to.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">Once we have this view of the desired state, we can t=
hen <span class=3D"bold">analyse needs</span>, starting by conducting a gap=
 analysis. This involves comparing the consensus model against what actuall=
y happens within the organisation. For example, if Director A and Director =
B agree that selling books to =E2=80=98contribute towards a better educated=
 society=E2=80=99 should be made a priority, they may come to the conclusio=
n that they should be liaising with online book club communities and runnin=
g webinars and other virtual events as well as selling books. They might, h=
owever, discover that none of these things is happening at present =E2=80=
=93 in which case there would be a gap that they could choose to address if=
 they so wished. Each gap is initially discovered at a fairly high level, s=
o further (more detailed) analysis is typically required, and it is likely =
that many options for plugging the gap will be uncovered.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">These options are further developed in the <span clas=
s=3D"bold">evaluate options</span> stage. In our example, if there is a nee=
d to engage with online book club communities, it is conceivable that there=
 will be a wide range of potential routes that could be taken. At one end, =
this might involve a deep collaboration with process and system integration=
 =E2=80=93 perhaps we could automatically receive details of each book club=
=E2=80=99s members and ship them a book each month at a discounted rate, an=
d twice a year we could arrange for a local author to attend a book club me=
eting. This would require fairly significant analysis and development of pr=
ocesses, organisational structure and IT. It may also impact roles and resp=
onsibilities within existing teams. Yet, at the other end of the spectrum, =
we may choose simply to ship a flyer with each book that promotes the book =
club community, <a id=3D"page_102"></a>which might be a simpler process cha=
nge. And, of course, there are many other options besides.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">Of course, project sponsors are unlikely to have the =
time or appetite to examine lengthy lists of options and are likely to want=
 to know which of the options the project team considers to be the best. Th=
erefore, it is important to consider not just whether the options are desir=
able but also whether they are feasible<span class=3D"italic">.</span> This=
 includes considering the business, technological and financial feasibility=
 of the change. Typically, this culminates in a business case which evaluat=
es a handful of options =E2=80=93 including a =E2=80=98do nothing=E2=80=99 =
option =E2=80=93 with a recommended option for the sponsor to consider.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">Assuming the sponsor agrees that some action should b=
e taken (and assuming the sponsor does not disband the project at this poin=
t), then more detailed analysis can start. In the <span class=3D"bold">defi=
ne requirements</span> stage, detailed information about what is required i=
s elicited, analysed, validated, documented and managed. Building on our ex=
ample, if the sponsor had decided that the business did indeed need closer =
links to online book clubs and had decided to commission the development of=
 an integrated website that allowed book club members to discuss books they=
 had bought (which we predicted would lead them to buy more books, increasi=
ng the business=E2=80=99 profits), effort would be required to uncover and =
document the requirements for the IT systems, new processes, new roles and =
any other changes. These might include requirements related to how people c=
an log in, the types of functionality required, specification of any manual=
 processes and so forth. This stage can be broken down further and describe=
d in more detail using BCS=E2=80=99s Requirements Engineering framework. Th=
is is outlined below.</p>
<h4 class=3D"h4">Requirements Engineering Framework</h4>
<p class=3D"noindent">The Requirements Engineering Framework (also from Pau=
l, Cadle and Yeates 2014) provides an overall pattern that can be used by a=
nalysts when operating within the <span class=3D"bold">define requirements<=
/span> stage. It is a flexible framework which outlines the core business a=
nalysis activities without mandating the <a id=3D"page_103"></a>specific to=
ols or techniques that a BA should use. That is to say, it very much says <=
span class=3D"bold">what</span> ought to be done but does not specify <span=
 class=3D"bold">how</span> it should be done =E2=80=93 nor does it specify =
<span class=3D"bold">how much</span> of each activity should be undertaken.=
 This is an important distinction, as the context of the situation will dri=
ve how tools and techniques are used. If we are procuring a solution, we ma=
y need a high-level list of requirements to be present in their entirety up=
 front, and this may need to be packaged as an RFP. This would lead to a ve=
ry different application of the framework compared with, say, changes to an=
 existing website that are undertaken in an adaptive way. In the former we =
are likely to work fairly sequentially: eliciting and analysing, then forma=
lising the documentation, prior to validating. In the latter we are likely =
to work in iterative cycles, perhaps validating prototypes for a particular=
 area, seeing how this looks once it has been developed, then considering o=
ther areas of functionality. This example illustrates that the model should=
 not be seen as strictly sequential and that activities can be conducted in=
 parallel. The arrows in <a href=3D"https://learning.oreilly.com/library/vi=
ew/business-analyst-/9781780174280/14_chapter04.xhtml#fig4-2">Figure 4.2</a=
> denote <span class=3D"bold">dependency</span> rather than <span class=3D"=
bold">sequence</span>; for example, before requirements can be analysed, th=
ey need to have been elicited. But that does <span class=3D"bold">not</span=
> mean that <span class=3D"bold">all</span> the requirements need to have b=
een elicited before analysis can start.</p>
<div class=3D"border1"></div>
<p class=3D"captionf"><a id=3D"fig4-2"></a><span class=3D"cap"><span class=
=3D"bold">Figure 4.2</span></span> <span class=3D"bold">The Requirements En=
gineering Framework</span> (Reproduced by permission of Assist Knowledge De=
velopment Ltd)</p>
