<h5 class=3D"h5"><span class=3D"bold"><span class=3D"italic">Example</span>=
</span></h5>
<p class=3D"noindenta">Building on our previous example, which involves eng=
ineering the requirements for a website that will enable book club members =
to discuss the books that they have bought, we would start by <span class=
=3D"bold">eliciting</span> requirements from relevant stakeholders. We migh=
t start with a workshop with our internal stakeholders, supplemented with d=
etailed interviews, to understand precisely what they envisage the website =
will do and any constraints that it might need to operate within (e.g. a le=
gal stakeholder may inform us that there is data protection legislation tha=
t we will need to adhere to =E2=80=93 an important requirement to capture s=
o that we can drill down into further detail). We would also benefit from a=
n external perspective, so we might send out questionnaires or even hold a =
focus group with a few friendly customers. This would help us to get a sens=
e of how (and whether) they would use the system and, crucially, what featu=
res they would find particularly useful. We would also need to establish wh=
ether there were any internal standards =E2=80=93 for example, brand standa=
rds, security standards and so forth =E2=80=93 which might constrain or gui=
de the solution.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">Elicitation is cyclical and ongoing =E2=80=93 it is r=
arely (if ever) a one-time event. Our initial elicitation activity would li=
kely uncover a whole range of =E2=80=98wants=E2=80=99. At this stage we wou=
ld often be, in essence, dealing with an unfiltered wish list. We might hav=
e a <a id=3D"page_107"></a>whole plethora of different written artefacts: m=
eeting minutes, sketches from workshops, partially formed process models an=
d so on. Our elicitation results would be unstructured and it is highly lik=
ely that there would be elements that were contradictory and incompatible w=
ith each other. This is where additional <span class=3D"bold">requirements<=
/span> <span class=3D"bold">analysis</span> activities are necessary.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">Requirements analysis involves bringing different req=
uirement artefacts together, increasing the level of precision and removing=
 any duplicate requirements. It is quite possible, building on our example,=
 that we will have a long list of potential requirements held in interview =
notes and so forth. Now is the time to tidy them up and start thinking abou=
t structuring and organising them. However, requirements analysis is much m=
ore than just housekeeping =E2=80=93 it can also be useful to create models=
 of the requirements which illustrate how different elements of the solutio=
n would work together. For example, a BA might create a functional model (s=
uch as a use-case diagram) to show the functionality, a data or information=
 model (such as a class diagram) to show the conceptual relationships and r=
ules governing the structure of the information stored by the solution, a p=
rototype to show the desired user experience, and so on. A BA might model t=
he whole solution or only part of it. Further information about different m=
odelling types can be found in the list of references at the back of this b=
ook.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">It is also likely that there will be different views =
regarding which requirements are most important. Our marketing colleagues m=
ight see the ability to automatically send bulk emails to members of the bo=
ok club as a key priority, whereas other stakeholders might suggest that it=
 is more important to deliver the core functionality first, allowing users =
to get used the system before we introduce marketing functionality and any =
other bells and whistles. Therefore, it is important to work with stakehold=
ers to prioritise the requirements. In a predictive, waterfall approach thi=
s may determine which requirements are delivered (or not). In an incrementa=
l approach, it is necessary to determine what is within the ultimate scope =
of the project but also what is within the scope of the next increment. Evo=
lutionary and agile approaches put <a id=3D"page_108"></a>particular emphas=
is on continual prioritisation, to ensure that =E2=80=98just enough=E2=80=
=99 is delivered at the right time, with a focus on delivering the features=
 that provide the most value soonest.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">Throughout this whole process, the requirements will =
be <span class=3D"bold">documented.</span> The type of documentation will v=
ary depending on the approach =E2=80=93 if we are outsourcing the delivery =
to a third party, we might need a complete list of requirements in a formal=
 document. If we are delivering using an adaptive approach, we might initia=
lly use lighter-weight documentation. Either way, the documentation becomes=
 appropriately structured through the analysis process, until it is ready t=
o be validated.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">In our example, <span class=3D"bold">validation</span=
> might involve a review with a cross-section of the stakeholder community =
(perhaps representatives from marketing, sales, customer service and so on)=
, and ultimate sign-off from the sponsor. Each participant validates the re=
quirements from a different angle =E2=80=93 a business stakeholder may vali=
date that the requirements represent their needs, whereas a technical team =
may validate that the requirements are suitably articulated for the next st=
age of the lifecycle to be implemented. Validation is likely to involve a f=
acilitated review session. In predictive, waterfall approaches, requirement=
s are baselined (i.e. a snapshot is taken against which any future changes =
can be considered) upon sign-off and further changes must be considered on =
their merits, typically through a change control process. Other approaches =
may absorb change in different ways =E2=80=93 for example, some agile appro=
aches typically allow change (providing it falls within the overall vision =
of the project) at any time, with the team appreciating that new requiremen=
ts mean that something else will not be delivered (unless budget and perhap=
s total project timescales are extended).</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">Throughout this entire process, requirements artefact=
s must be well <span class=3D"bold">managed.</span> There is nothing more f=
rustrating than finding different stakeholders are looking at different ver=
sions of the same requirement, so ensure there is a common repository (whet=
her using a specific requirements management or <a id=3D"page_109"></a>comp=
uter-aided software engineering tool, or some form of spreadsheet or other =
document). This also involves ensuring that requirements can be uniquely id=
entified, through the use of a persistent unique identifier, and that appro=
priate version control is employed. Ensuring that relationships between req=
uirements are maintained is also crucial, so that they can be traced. Addit=
ionally, it is important to ensure that they are stored securely so that on=
ly those with a genuine business need can view and edit them.</p>
<h4 class=3D"h4">IIBA<sup>=C2=AE</sup> Knowledge Areas</h4>
<p class=3D"noindent">IIBA<sup>=C2=AE</sup>=E2=80=99s Business Analysis Bod=
y of Knowledge (<span class=3D"italic">BABOK<sup>=C2=AE</sup> Guide</span>;=
 see International Institute of Business Analysis 2015) was developed indep=
endently of the BCS framework, but as you would expect with a profession th=
at is maturing, the two are similar in intent and can be seen as being comp=
lementary rather than divergent. BABOK<sup>=C2=AE</sup> outlines six Knowle=
dge Areas, plus a range of underlying competencies and perspectives. Knowle=
dge Areas are described as representing =E2=80=98areas of specific business=
 analysis expertise that encompass several tasks=E2=80=99 (International In=
stitute of Business Analysis 2015). Each underlying task is typically condu=
cted at least once, although often multiple times, in any single business a=
nalysis engagement. As with the BCS framework described in the previous sec=
tion, the IIBA<sup>=C2=AE</sup> framework is flexible =E2=80=93 it may be t=
hat on one project each task is conducted very formally with detailed docum=
entation created. On a smaller and less risky project, tasks may be less fo=
rmal, with lighter-weight documentation.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">The six key Knowledge Areas are illustrated in <a hre=
f=3D"https://learning.oreilly.com/library/view/business-analyst-/9781780174=
280/14_chapter04.xhtml#fig4-3">Figure 4.3</a>.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">Each Knowledge Area is outlined in <a href=3D"https:/=
/learning.oreilly.com/library/view/business-analyst-/9781780174280/14_chapt=
er04.xhtml#tab4-3">Table 4.3</a>.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">You will notice that <a href=3D"https://learning.orei=
lly.com/library/view/business-analyst-/9781780174280/14_chapter04.xhtml#fig=
4-3">Figure 4.3</a> does not imply a linear relationship between activities=
 =E2=80=93 this is intentional, as activities within each area may take pla=
ce several times during a given project or initiative. There is also no fix=
ed order or sequence, although projects typically start with strategy analy=
sis (a new idea or opportunity) or solution evaluation (a problem with an e=
xisting solution, which then leads to strategy analysis).</p>
