ight=3D"590" data-mfp-src=3D"/library/view/business-analyst-/9781780174280/=
images/fig4-3.jpg"></p>
<div class=3D"border1"></div>
<p class=3D"captiont"><a id=3D"tab4-3"></a><span class=3D"cap"><span class=
=3D"bold">Table 4.3</span></span> <span class=3D"bold">The BABOK<sup>=C2=AE=
</sup> Knowledge Areas</span></p>
<table style=3D"width:100%" class=3D"table-se">
<colgroup>
<col style=3D"width:20%">
<col style=3D"width:80%">
</colgroup>
<thead>
<tr>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s1"><span class=3D"bold">Kno=
wledge Area</span></td>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s1"><span class=3D"bold">Bri=
ef Description</span></td>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">Business Analysis Plannin=
g and Monitoring</td>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;">
<p class=3D"bull-s"><span class=3D"bul-s">=E2=80=A2</span> This Knowledge A=
rea involves planning the overall business analysis approach and how to eng=
age and work with stakeholders.</p>
<p class=3D"bull-s"><span class=3D"bul-s">=E2=80=A2</span> It also involves=
 assessing how the BA work will be governed and where BA documents and arte=
facts will be stored.</p>
<p class=3D"bull-s"><span class=3D"bul-s">=E2=80=A2</span> Additionally, it=
 covers the ongoing monitoring of BA activities, including identifying any =
ways of improving the quality of the analysis and the performance of the an=
alyst team.</p>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s"><a id=3D"page_111"></a>El=
icitation and Collaboration</td>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;">
<p class=3D"bull-s"><span class=3D"bul-s">=E2=80=A2</span> This Knowledge A=
rea involves the preparation and carrying out of elicitation activities, an=
d the confirmation of elicitation results.</p>
<p class=3D"bull-s"><span class=3D"bul-s">=E2=80=A2</span> It includes elic=
itation early in the business change lifecycle (where a problem or opportun=
ity is being investigated) as well as more detailed elicitation that takes =
place later on.</p>
<p class=3D"bull-s"><span class=3D"bul-s">=E2=80=A2</span> It also includes=
 ongoing communication and collaboration with stakeholders.</p>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s"><a id=3D"page_112"></a>Re=
quirements Life Cycle Management</td>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;">
<p class=3D"bull-s"><span class=3D"bul-s">=E2=80=A2</span> This Knowledge A=
rea includes the tracing and general maintenance of requirements.</p>
<p class=3D"bull-s"><span class=3D"bul-s">=E2=80=A2</span> It involves prio=
ritising requirements.</p>
<p class=3D"bull-s"><span class=3D"bul-s">=E2=80=A2</span> It also includes=
 seeking (and achieving) approval of requirements, and assessing requiremen=
t changes.</p>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">Strategy Analysis</td>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;">
<p class=3D"bull-s"><span class=3D"bul-s">=E2=80=A2</span> Often this Knowl=
edge Area is related to work carried out up front to understand underlying =
problems and opportunities.</p>
<p class=3D"bull-s"><span class=3D"bul-s">=E2=80=A2</span> It includes anal=
ysing the current state, defining the desired future state and assessing an=
y risks that may emerge.</p>
<p class=3D"bull-s"><span class=3D"bul-s">=E2=80=A2</span> It includes defi=
ning a =E2=80=98change strategy=E2=80=99, which will likely involve evaluat=
ing several options and recommending an approach in a business case or equi=
valent document.</p>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">Requirements Analysis and=
 Design Definition</td>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;">
<p class=3D"bull-s"><span class=3D"bul-s">=E2=80=A2</span> This Knowledge A=
rea includes the specification, modelling and documentation of requirements=
.</p>
<p class=3D"bull-s"><span class=3D"bul-s">=E2=80=A2</span> It also involves=
 the verification (quality checking) and validation (ensuring alignment wit=
h objectives that are valued by the business) of relevant artefacts.</p>
<p class=3D"bull-s"><span class=3D"bul-s">=E2=80=A2</span> It includes defi=
nition of a =E2=80=98requirements architecture=E2=80=99 =E2=80=93 that is, =
defining how different requirement artefacts connect together conceptually.=
 For example, this might define how different models relate to each other, =
how they connect to any textual requirements artefacts and so forth.</p>
<p class=3D"bull-s"><span class=3D"bul-s">=E2=80=A2</span> It covers the de=
finition and recommendation of design options. It should be noted that BABO=
K<sup>=C2=AE</sup> acknowledges that analysis often blurs into design =E2=
=80=93 for example, detailed specification of a process might involve defin=
ing the physical steps which will be undertaken by those who are involved i=
n the execution of the process. This implies a strong element of both defin=
ition and design. However, it should be noted that BAs do not normally unde=
rtake IT technical design work. The extent to which BAs are involved with d=
esign will depend on the context, the type of problem or opportunity, and t=
he options being pursued.</p>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s"><a id=3D"page_113"></a>So=
lution Evaluation</td>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;">
<p class=3D"bull-s"><span class=3D"bul-s">=E2=80=A2</span> This Knowledge A=
rea considers the tasks undertaken by BAs in relation to solutions that hav=
e been constructed (built).</p>
<p class=3D"bull-s"><span class=3D"bul-s">=E2=80=A2</span> It includes meas=
uring and analysing solution performance =E2=80=93 either of a solution tha=
t has been deployed or of a proof of concept.</p>
<p class=3D"bull-s"><span class=3D"bul-s">=E2=80=A2</span> It covers assess=
ment of any (internal) enterprise limitations that are inhibiting the perfo=
rmance of the solution.</p>
<p class=3D"bull-s"><span class=3D"bul-s">=E2=80=A2</span> It encompasses m=
aking any recommendations to improve the performance of the solution and re=
alise additional benefits.</p>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<h5 class=3D"h5"><span class=3D"bold"><span class=3D"italic">Example</span>=
</span></h5>
<p class=3D"noindenta">As soon as a BA becomes involved, they are likely to=
 start by <span class=3D"bold">planning</span> their approach and then <spa=
n class=3D"bold">eliciting</span> the core need and business requirements. =
Next they will undertake <span class=3D"bold">strategy analysis</span>. The=
 BA will seek to understand why the project is beneficial, and will also id=
entify key objectives and areas of perceived benefit. The existing situatio=
n will be examined, and options developed and explored. A recommended optio=
n will be presented in a business case or similar document. Alongside all o=
f this activity, <span class=3D"bold">requirements lifecycle management</sp=
an> is taking place =E2=80=93 albeit with high-level business requirements.=
</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">Assuming the business case or equivalent artefact is =
approved, further <span class=3D"bold">business analysis planning</span> wi=
ll take place, and more <a id=3D"page_114"></a>detailed <span class=3D"bold=
">elicitation</span> activities will be undertaken =E2=80=93 this time focu=
sing on solution requirements. Detailed requirements will be defined using =
the tasks in the <span class=3D"bold">Requirements Analysis and Design Defi=
nition</span> Knowledge Area and, of course, requirements will continue to =
be <span class=3D"bold">managed</span>. These activities will continue, typ=
ically iteratively, throughout the project. The timing and nature of these =
activities will vary depending on the project approach that has been adopte=
d.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">After the project has been implemented, <span class=
=3D"bold">solution evaluation</span> will take place to judge the efficacy =
and efficiency of the implemented change. If the solution is not generating=
 the types of benefit that were anticipated, further analysis may be needed=
 =E2=80=93 and further <span class=3D"bold">strategy analysis</span> may me=
an that another project is defined.</p>
<h3 class=3D"h3" id=3D"sec26"><a id=3D"h38"></a>COMMONLY USED TOOLS AND TEC=
HNIQUES</h3>
<p class=3D"noindent">A survey by IIBA<sup>=C2=AE</sup>=E2=80=99s UK Chapte=
r (International Institute of Business Analysis UK Chapter 2015), based on =
nearly 670 responses, showed that the top five most frequently used busines=
s analysis techniques are:</p>
<div class=3D"top">
<p class=3D"bull"><span class=3D"bul">=E2=80=A2</span> requirements worksho=
ps;</p>
<p class=3D"bull"><span class=3D"bul">=E2=80=A2</span> interviewing;</p>
<p class=3D"bull"><span class=3D"bul">=E2=80=A2</span> MoSCoW (must have, s=
hould have, could have, won=E2=80=99t have this time) prioritisation;</p>
<p class=3D"bull"><span class=3D"bul">=E2=80=A2</span> use-case modelling;<=
/p>
<p class=3D"bull"><span class=3D"bul">=E2=80=A2</span> user stories.</p>
</div>
<p class=3D"noindent">These were narrowly followed by mock-ups (a form of p=
rototyping). We might draw the conclusion from this list that the most comm=
on techniques refer to the <span class=3D"bold">elicitation</span>, <span c=
lass=3D"bold">analysis</span> and <span class=3D"bold">definition</span> of=
 requirements of various kinds =E2=80=93 whether high-level business requir=
ements or detailed solution requirements.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">However, whilst these techniques might be the most co=
mmonly used, there are many others. The specific context in which a practit=
ioner is operating, along with the practitioner=E2=80=99s <a id=3D"page_115=
"></a>judgement, will help to determine the most appropriate techniques for=
 a given situation. <a href=3D"https://learning.oreilly.com/library/view/bu=
siness-analyst-/9781780174280/14_chapter04.xhtml#tab4-4">Table 4.4</a> list=
s some of the more frequently used business analysis tools and techniques a=
long with a very brief descriptions of each. Readers who are interested in =
finding out more will find more detailed discussions of these techniques in=
 the BCS books <span class=3D"italic">Business Analysis</span> (Paul, Cadle=
 and Yeates 2014) and <span class=3D"italic">Business Analysis Techniques: =
99 Essential Tools for Success</span> (Cadle, Paul and Turner 2014) as well=
 as in the IIBA<sup>=C2=AE</sup>=E2=80=99s <span class=3D"italic">A</span> =
<span class=3D"italic">Guide to the Business Analysis Body of Knowledge (BA=
BOK</span><sup>=C2=AE</sup> <span class=3D"italic">Guide) v3</span> (2015).=
</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">Please note: these techniques are presented in alphab=
etical order, and their order does not imply importance or popularity.</p>
<div class=3D"border1"></div>
<p class=3D"captiont"><a id=3D"tab4-4"></a><span class=3D"cap"><span class=
=3D"bold">Table 4.4</span></span> <span class=3D"bold">Frequently used busi=
ness analysis techniques</span></p>
<table style=3D"width:100%" class=3D"table-se">
<colgroup>
<col style=3D"width:20%">
<col style=3D"width:80%">
</colgroup>
<thead>
<tr>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s1"><span class=3D"bold">Too=
l or Technique</span></td>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s1"><span class=3D"bold">Des=
cription</span></td>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">Acceptance and evaluation=
 criteria</td>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">A form of quantification =
or scale of measure for a requirement, which will allow test cases to be de=
veloped so that a solution can be objectively tested to see whether the req=
uirement has been met.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">Backlog management</td>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">The continual management =
and prioritisation of a backlog of work or requirements, in collaboration w=
ith other business stakeholders, typically (but not exclusively) in an adap=
tive or agile environment.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">Balanced scorecard</td>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">A technique that facilita=
tes the elicitation and definition of critical success factors and key perf=
ormance indicators at various levels =E2=80=93 e.g. organisational, departm=
ental and project =E2=80=93 typically using standard categories such as cus=
tomer, financial, internal, and learning and growth. See Kaplan and Norton =
(1996) for further information.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s"><a id=3D"page_116"></a>Br=
ainstorming</td>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">The use of divergent thin=
king techniques that allow the generation of ideas. Typically used to gener=
ate potential requirements, solutions, risks and so forth.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">Business cases</td>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">A business case should pr=
ovide a compelling case for change, considering the overall desirability an=
d feasibility of various options. A BA should not own the business case, no=
r would they be the ultimate decision maker, but a great deal of analysis i=
s required to put the case together. Therefore, BAs are often involved in t=
he creation and presentation of business cases.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">Business perspective anal=
ysis</td>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">The use of techniques to =
understand the perspectives of a stakeholder in terms of what a business sy=
stem ought to <span class=3D"bold">do</span> and the stakeholder=E2=80=99s =
perspectives on <span class=3D"bold">why</span> that system exists. Possibl=
e techniques include CATWOE (customer, actor, transformation, <span class=
=3D"italic">Weltanschauung</span> or worldview, owner, environment), PARADE=
 (perspective or point of view, activity, recipient, actor, decision maker,=
 environment) and root definitions. (CATWOE and =E2=80=98root definitions=
=E2=80=99 originate from Checkland=E2=80=99s Soft Systems Methodology; read=
ers interested in these topics may wish to consult Checkland 1999. PARADE w=
as derived from Checkland by Paul Turner in Cadle, Paul and Turner 2014.)</=
td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">Business rules analysis</=
td>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">The understanding and doc=
umentation of the definitional and behavioural rules that exist within the =
business. These rules often constrain or shape the way that work is underta=
ken.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s"><a id=3D"page_117"></a>Co=
nceptual modelling</td>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">The use of techniques suc=
h as business activity modelling to create a view of a set of business acti=
vities from a stakeholder=E2=80=99s idealised perspective. This is usually =
used to find accommodation or (if possible) consensus between conflicting s=
takeholder views within a situation of interest.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">Context diagrams</td>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">High-level diagrams which=
 abstract away details of how a system performs its underlying transformati=
on but that consider the types of interaction that external actors (such as=
 users or external systems) have with the system under consideration.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">Data dictionary</td>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">A compilation of definiti=
ons of common business meanings of data elements captured by information pr=
ocessing systems (automated or manual).</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">Data modelling</td>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">Definition of a model sho=
wing the different types of data that are important in a particular busines=
s situation and the relationships and rules that exist (these include class=
 diagrams and entity relationship diagrams).</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">Document analysis</td>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">Elicitation of informatio=
n about a business situation by examining documentation that is used within=
 the business.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">Financial analysis and in=
vestment appraisal</td>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">Financial analysis is typ=
ically carried out as part of a business case, usually with the support of =
a predefined template, and often by a suitably experienced member of the pr=
oject management office (or a project accountant). It involves assessing pr=
ojects using a variety of appraisal metrics. Includes payback period, net p=
resent value and internal rate of return.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s"><a id=3D"page_118"></a>Fo=
cus groups</td>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">Groups in which customers=
 (or other stakeholders) are assembled to discuss a particular issue or pro=
blem, in order to elicit ideas or feedback. Can also be used to gauge respo=
nses to a potential solution or prototype.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">Glossary</td>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">A shared set of definitio=
ns of key business terminology. A good glossary helps to ensure that commun=
ication is more succinct and more precise amongst stakeholders.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">Interviews</td>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">Typically, one-on-one mee=
tings with stakeholders to elicit information through structured (or semi-s=
tructured) questioning.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">Mind mapping</td>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">A technique for documenti=
ng a rich, =E2=80=98messy=E2=80=99 situation in a semi-structured way.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">Non-functional requiremen=
ts analysis</td>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">The analysis of non-funct=
ional elements of a solution, such as performance, security, scalability an=
d so forth.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">Observation</td>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">Observing (viewing or wat=
ching) a stakeholder or team, undertaken to understand more about how work =
is carried out.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">Prioritisation</td>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">Assessment of the relativ=
e priority of requirements against each other, taking into consideration th=
e overall objectives and value that the requirements will help to achieve. =
This often involves negotiating and managing conflicting views amongst stak=
eholders.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s"><a id=3D"page_119"></a>Pr=
ocess analysis and modelling</td>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">Definition of a model sho=
wing how a repeatable set of activities happen within a business. Can inclu=
de process modelling at various levels of abstraction, including process fl=
ows, swim-lane diagrams, task descriptions or procedure manuals, and so for=
th.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">Prototyping</td>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">The creation of a mock-up=
 of some element of the proposed solution. For an IT solution, this could i=
nclude screen mock-ups, report mock-ups and so forth. For other types of in=
itiative, BAs may work with other specialists to produce prototypes (e.g. a=
 warehouse move may require consideration of where and how stock will be la=
id out =E2=80=93 this could potentially be prototyped and modelled to varyi=
ng levels of precision using specialist software).</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">Rich pictures</td>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">A technique for documenti=
ng a rich, =E2=80=98messy=E2=80=99 situation in a pictorial format, showing=
 =E2=80=98softer=E2=80=99 aspects such as culture and conflict (as well as =
more tangible aspects such as structure).</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">Root cause analysis</td>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">A family of techniques, i=
ncluding 5 Whys, fishbone diagrams, multiple cause diagrams and so forth, t=
hat allow a BA to uncover and understand the reasons why a problem has occu=
rred or is occurring.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">Stakeholder analysis</td>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">A family of techniques us=
ed to identify, categorise and engage stakeholders within (and, where neces=
sary, outside) an organisation.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s"><a id=3D"page_120"></a>Su=
rveys and questionnaires</td>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">Mechanism for eliciting i=
nformation from a large and typically distributed stakeholder community.</t=
d>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">SWOT analysis</td>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">An acronym that refers to=
 assessing the strengths, weaknesses, opportunities and threats in a busine=
ss situation. Often used in combination with other external and internal en=
vironmental analysis techniques.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">Use-case models including=
 scenarios</td>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">System use-case models sh=
ow interactions between an actor and a system. This may include interaction=
s between a user and a system, and may also represent other actors (e.g. sy=
stems).
<p class=3D"tab-s">Use-case models often include related scenarios. Scenari=
os show, step by step, what happens when a particular interaction between a=
n actor and a system takes place. Exceptions and alternative paths are also=
 documented.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">User stories</td>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">Short, succinct placehold=
ers for requirements. Often articulated in a standard format, such as: =E2=
=80=98As a=E2=80=A6 I want=E2=80=A6 so that=E2=80=A6=E2=80=99. Acceptance c=
riteria are added to a user story to ensure that it is precise and testable=
.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">Vendor assessment</td>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">The assessment of varying=
 potential (external) solution options, typically through an RFI and RFP pr=
ocess, or an ITT process.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">Workshops</td>
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" class=3D"tab-s">Facilitated meetings, typ=
ically with a range of representative stakeholders present, with a specific=
 defined focus. Often used for eliciting or reviewing requirements.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p class=3D"noindent"><a id=3D"page_121"></a>This list, by its very nature,=
 is partial and focuses on some of the more commonly used techniques. Yet i=
t illustrates the rich range of tools and techniques available to BAs, whic=
h raises a further relevant and interesting question: Does a BA need to be =
an expert in <span class=3D"bold">all</span> possible techniques?</p>
<h4 class=3D"h4">Context is king</h4>
<p class=3D"noindent">Whilst a BA must maintain an awareness and working kn=
owledge of a wide range of techniques, it is unlikely that an individual pr=
actitioner will need to be fully versed in every single technique. Particul=
arly when a BA is beginning their career, it is likely that other more expe=
rienced analysts will be available to provide guidance on <span class=3D"bo=
ld">which</span> techniques are most suitable for a given situation whilst =
also providing practical help on <span class=3D"bold">how</span> to apply t=
he techniques.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">As a practitioner=E2=80=99s career develops, it is li=
kely that they will need to have a more detailed knowledge and experience o=
f a wider range of tools and techniques. This is important for a number of =
reasons:</p>
<div class=3D"top">
<p class=3D"number"><span class=3D"num"><span class=3D"bold">1.</span></spa=
n> <span class=3D"bold">Choosing an appropriate tool for the job:</span> Se=
nior BAs will be involved with understanding the business situation and sel=
ecting the analysis tools and techniques that are most relevant to the cont=
ext. If a practitioner is not aware of a technique, then they will be unabl=
e to choose it (the technique may be completely outside their awareness, an=
 =E2=80=98unknown unknown=E2=80=99). Left unchecked, this may result in oth=
er, less appropriate and less effective techniques being used.</p>
<p class=3D"number"><span class=3D"num"><span class=3D"bold">2.</span></spa=
n> <span class=3D"bold">Adapting to a context:</span> As alluded to earlier=
 in this chapter, no two projects are identical, and contexts can vary dram=
atically. One project may require precision, accuracy and flawless quality.=
 Another may need to get something out quickly, with the acceptance that it=
 may not be perfect (and may be polished and refined after release). The co=
ntext may drive the analysis approach taken, the types <a id=3D"page_122"><=
/a>(and number) of resources engaged, and the tools and techniques that are=
 used. This in turn may have a knock-on impact on other project resource an=
d scheduling requirements. We may need significant chunks of stakeholder ti=
me for elicitation activities, or we may require collocated office space fo=
r collaborative working.</p>
<p class=3D"number"><span class=3D"num"><span class=3D"bold">3.</span></spa=
n> <span class=3D"bold">Providing guidance to other less experienced practi=
tioners:</span> As a BA=E2=80=99s career progresses, it is likely that =E2=
=80=93 either implicitly or explicitly =E2=80=93 there will be an expectati=
on that they will provide guidance or even mentoring to other less experien=
ced members of the team. It is therefore essential that they maintain an up=
-to-date view on the breadth of tools and techniques available.</p>
<p class=3D"number"><span class=3D"num"><span class=3D"bold">4.</span></spa=
n> <span class=3D"bold">Variety of initiatives:</span> As a practitioner be=
comes more experienced, it is likely they will have exposure to a wider ran=
ge of initiatives =E2=80=93 including IT change, people change, organisatio=
nal change, culture change, location change and many other aspects too. Som=
e of the types of technique that are most relevant in, say, a small project=
 to update the branding on an existing website will differ from those requi=
red to assess the impact of a major merger between two companies. Therefore=
, continually enhancing and expanding one=E2=80=99s toolkit is crucial.</p>
</div>
<p class=3D"noindent">However, it is extraordinarily rare that a practition=
er needs to be an expert on <span class=3D"bold">all</span> conceivable ana=
lysis techniques. It is usual for experienced practitioners to become very =
familiar with the most commonly used techniques whilst maintaining a workin=
g knowledge of others, so that those other techniques can be deployed when =
required. Equally, it is perfectly normal for practitioners to look up info=
rmation as and when they need it =E2=80=93 this can be particularly useful =
to refresh one=E2=80=99s memory. If a practitioner has not drawn a use-case=
 diagram for some time, and cannot remember the precise notation for some o=
f the more advanced concepts, they may well refer to a trusted resource or =
ask a colleague for clarification.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent"><a id=3D"page_123"></a>It should also be noted that n=
either BCS nor IIBA<sup>=C2=AE</sup> purport to have a list of all possible=
 and conceivable techniques. Both organisations catalogue information about=
 common techniques, but some practitioners may use other techniques in the =
course of their analysis, perhaps techniques they have learned from other d=
isciplines or in previous roles. An example might be an analyst who has pre=
viously worked in a sales role using certain techniques from the world of s=
ales to analyse a stakeholder=E2=80=99s needs and wants. Alternatively, som=
eone with a background in systems thinking might use a range of techniques =
that are complementary to those commonly used in business analysis. Another=
 example might be a BA who has worked closely with a UX consultant and uses=
 the opportunity to learn from their colleague and use certain techniques i=
n their next project.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">These are examples of situations where BAs can take o=
pportunities to engage with (and learn from) other communities. This cross-=
pollination of techniques is to be encouraged; not only does it help to bui=
ld mutual understanding but it also allows techniques and experience to be =
shared. However, BAs do need to be careful to ensure that techniques are ge=
nuinely being used from an <span class=3D"bold">analysis</span> perspective=
. We might observe our project management colleagues using a visual techniq=
ue to track dependencies. This might prove useful for the analysis planning=
 too; however, if we started to use it for the whole project, we might find=
 that we have temporarily removed our =E2=80=98BA=E2=80=99 hat and instead =
put on a =E2=80=98project manager=E2=80=99 hat. There is nothing inherently=
 wrong with this, providing it is done deliberately and that the practition=
er who is switching hats genuinely has the relevant skills and experience t=
o undertake both roles.</p>
<h4 class=3D"h4">Analysis does not happen in a vacuum</h4>
<p class=3D"noindent">Whilst the focus of this chapter is very much on busi=
ness analysis frameworks, tools and techniques, it is important to note tha=
t analysis does not happen in a vacuum. Whilst analytical techniques themse=
lves are useful ways of engaging with, analysing and documenting a situatio=
n, a set of needs, <a id=3D"page_124"></a>a set of requirements, or a set o=
f potential options, there is a wider set of skills and competencies that a=
 BA must possess. This is recognised by BCS and IIBA<sup>=C2=AE</sup>, both=
 of which highlight a range of additional key areas in which a practitioner=
 needs to be proficient.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">Of particular merit are <span class=3D"bold">interper=
sonal skills.</span> Many techniques simply will not work well at all if a =
practitioner cannot interact and build rapport with a range of relevant sta=
keholders. These skills include listening, working to understand and empath=
ise with each stakeholder, negotiation, assertiveness, tactfully challengin=
g, and influencing. This often involves putting ourselves in the shoes of a=
 different stakeholder and considering how they view a particular problemat=
ic situation or proposed course of action. As a BA=E2=80=99s career progres=
ses, influencing and the ability to lead change collaboratively become incr=
easingly important.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">Remaining curious about the business situation and ou=
r stakeholders and being prepared to challenge and question are absolutely =
crucial. This is illustrated in the following quote from a BA manager inter=
viewed for this book:</p>
<div class=3D"blockquote">
<p class=3D"noindent">Curiosity is crucial for any business analyst. It=E2=
=80=99s important to think like an analyst, to be constantly questioning an=
d challenging. (Michelle Shakesheff, Business Analysis Manager, Zurich Insu=
rance)</p>
</div>
<p class=3D"noindent">These all are skills that practitioners continually b=
uild throughout their career =E2=80=93 whilst senior practitioners may be m=
ore experienced in these areas, there will always be new contexts and situa=
tions that provide a challenge and the opportunity to learn. In particular,=
 as an individual=E2=80=99s career progresses, it is likely that it will be=
 necessary for them to liaise and work with a wider range of stakeholders, =
who will often span multiple companies and countries. This requires an appr=
eciation of different types of corporate culture along with an understandin=
g of how national cultures may differ (and where this might lead to misunde=
rstandings). Both of these types of culture may affect the types of analysi=
s approach that <a id=3D"page_125"></a>are feasible and the techniques that=
 are used, and will have an impact on stakeholder engagement and communicat=
ion.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent"><span class=3D"bold">Leadership</span> =E2=80=93 whet=
her of oneself or others =E2=80=93 also becomes increasingly relevant as a =
BA=E2=80=99s career progresses. In particular, it is likely that more senio=
r BAs will be responsible for defining the analysis approach, shaping the w=
ork and leading others within a project. Several different types of leaders=
hip are discussed in <a href=3D"https://learning.oreilly.com/library/view/b=
usiness-analyst-/9781780174280/13_chapter03.xhtml">Chapter 3</a>. Leadershi=
p at all levels requires <span class=3D"bold">resilience.</span> Throughout=
 a BA=E2=80=99s career, they will be collaborating and facilitating, but th=
is also involves challenging entrenched positions. There will inevitably be=
 conflict, and sometimes in times of difficulty the spotlight will be focus=
ed purely on the person asking the difficult questions. It is essential in =
these circumstances to remain calm, confident and focused on the objectives=
 of the initiative and the outcomes that the organisation is seeking. Of co=
urse, all perspectives should be considered, but it is important to avoid s=
ituations where =E2=80=98those who shout the loudest=E2=80=99 determine the=
 direction. A BA=E2=80=99s analysis will often allow them to shine new ligh=
t on situations, backed up by relevant investigations and data, and this ca=
n help to drive very collaborative decisions. Yet we should not expect a co=
mpletely smooth ride!</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">Additionally, it is important that BAs gain and maint=
ain sufficient <span class=3D"bold">business knowledge</span>. As mentioned=
 in <a href=3D"https://learning.oreilly.com/library/view/business-analyst-/=
9781780174280/12_chapter02.xhtml">Chapter 2</a>, where the T-shaped busines=
s analyst was discussed, it is not necessary for a BA to be a SME; however,=
 we must be able to assimilate enough information to hold a credible conver=
sation about the domain in which we are operating. We should know the core =
terminology, how the business operates (broadly speaking) and so forth. It =
is also vital that we have a good knowledge of general business issues so t=
hat we can interact and converse with a wide range of stakeholders. Some of=
 this knowledge may have been gained in previous roles or project engagemen=
ts, and it is important that we continue to develop and nurture the knowled=
ge needed for the domain in which we are operating.</p>
<h3 class=3D"h3" id=3D"sec27"><a id=3D"h39"></a><a id=3D"page_126"></a>SUMM=
ARY</h3>
<p class=3D"noindent">When working on an engagement, a BA rarely needs to s=
tart from scratch and reinvent the wheel. There are a wide range of framewo=
rks, tools and techniques that can be used or adapted. This chapter discuss=
ed the Business Analysis Process Model and the Requirements Engineering Fra=
mework from the BCS book <span class=3D"italic">Business Analysis</span> (P=
aul, Cadle and Yeates 2014) and the Knowledge Areas from IIBA<sup>=C2=AE</s=
up>=E2=80=99s <span class=3D"italic">BABOK</span><sup>=C2=AE</sup> <span cl=
ass=3D"italic">Guide v3</span> (International Institute of Business Analysi=
s 2015). These are all well-known and well-used frameworks.</p>
<p class=3D"noindent">This chapter briefly discussed a range of tools and t=
echniques, although it should be noted that this is by no means intended as=
 an exhaustive list. Context is always king when it comes to business analy=
sis, and we should be prepared to adapt our approach, bringing in new tools=
 and techniques when needed. We certainly should not paint by numbers!</p>
